Anubis: The jackal-headed god Anubis, associated with mummification and the afterlife, typically oversaw the scale and guided the deceased through the process.
The Ceremony: After death, the deceased's soul would journey to the Hall of Two Truths. Here, their heart, which the Egyptians believed was the seat of the soul, intellect, and memory, was placed on one side of a great scale.
Thoth: The god of writing, knowledge, and wisdom, Thoth (often depicted with the head of an ibis or a baboon) stood nearby to meticulously record the results of the weighing. He acted as the divine scribe and sometimes as an advocate.
